In essence, we need renewables for a controlled soft landing. But the harsh reality is that, for now, and in the foreseeable future, the energy transition is not going well and has poor overall prospects.Build community resilience. Learn to get by with less.

The transition from fossil fuel to renewables faces an uphill battle. Still, this switch is an essential stopgap strategy to keep electricity grids up and running, at least on a minimal scale, as civilization inevitably turns away from a depleting store of oil and gas.

Wind turbines and solar panels are also vulnerable to weather extremes. Cold, cloudy days with virtually no wind spell trouble for regions heavily reliant on renewable energy. High temps reduce panels’ efficiency, and hurricanes and storm surges can cripple offshore wind farms.

Heavy rain and flooding can pose risks for both hydro and nuclear power. In March 2019, severe flooding in southern and western Africa, following Cyclone Idai, damaged two major hydro plants in Malawi, cutting off power to parts of the country for several days.

A study published in February 2022 in the journal @Water_MDPI found that droughts (which are becoming more frequent and severe with climate change) could create challenges for U.S. hydropower in Montana, Nevada, Texas, Arizona, California, Arkansas, and Oklahoma.

Meanwhile, a similarly grim story unfolded in Germany, as a record drought reduced the water flow in the Rhine River to levels that crippled European trade, halting shipments of diesel and coal, and threatening the operations of both hydroelectric and nuclear power plants.

During the summer of 2022, China experienced its most intense heat wave in six decades. At the same time, a drought-induced power crisis forced Contemporary Amperex Technology Co., the world’s top battery maker, to close manufacturing plants in China’s Sichuan province.

@mayajuman @NSF @Gates_Cambridge @Yale @alaskamuseum @mcgillu @yale_eeb @YaleBiosphere @IUCN_SMSG @EEB_POC Thanks for tagging us!  Congratulations!Happy to provide #NSERCsupport!

Thanks also to @NSF, @NSERC_CRSNG, @Gates_Cambridge for funding, and to my twitterless coauthors (@Yale, @alaskamuseum, @mcgillu) for all their support 🌴🐀⌛️☀️🌧️🏝️📈🤓@yale_eeb @YaleBiosphere @IUCN_SMSG @EEB_POC (19/end)

On that note, our dataset included specimens from 16 museums. Big thx to curators/staff @AMNH, @CarnegieMNH, @FieldMuseum, @kunhm, @NHMLA, @MCZHarvard, @Le_Museum, @MVZUCB, @NHM_London, @ROMtoronto, @Senckenberg, @UMMNH, @NMNH, @yalepeabody (❤️), @mfnberlin, @NHM_Denmark (18/19)

This work would simply not be possible without data from historical museum specimens. Our study emphasizes the necessity of continued collecting during a time of unprecedented global change and impacts on biodiversity #CollectionsAreEssential (17/19)

Mechanisms are unclear, but we know this region has changed recently. Change is heterogeneous across latitude/islands (⬇️ temp, rain, forest/urban cover at start + end of 20th c.). Studies of size must account for time, or else might miss hidden patterns/inflection points (16/19) https://t.co/oVAjEjUtun

Most importantly: we’ve always known rules are just “rules”, but here we suggest that their magnitude and slope can shift over time. Many studies have tried to use Bergmann’s rule to predict responses to warming, but could climate change be rewriting the rules themselves? (15/19)

So: a highly consistent signal of body size increasing w/ temp, across both space (latitude) and time (climate change). Decreases in body size =/= universal response to warming! Our locality map ⬇️ is color-coded by historical temp, and point size = relative body size (14/19) https://t.co/kgsQlB5tkE

We also associated historical climate and land-use data w/ all possible specimens. Temperature was positively associated with body size, and a temp-precipitation interaction suggests that in wetter climates, the relationship b/w temp and body size is even steeper ☀️🌧️ (13/19) https://t.co/wXXvtCebdT

What factors might be driving island body size? We analyzed our island dataset separately and found that distance to the mainland, and not island area, explained the most variance in body size: Northern Treeshrews are smaller on more distant islands (12/19) https://t.co/IKRZPpxP1g

We also found once again that island individuals show the opposite change over time. Massive caveat here that our island sampling is very spatially and temporally biased, so this needs further investigation 🏝️🔎 (11/19) https://t.co/CUDkLt8s2i

🚨 And for the first time in *any species* we demonstrate that Bergmann’s rule has reversed – quickly and recently! B’s rule is upheld by specimens from the late 19th c. (when the rule was described), but the trend reversed by the mid 20th c., growing steeper over time 📉 (10/19) https://t.co/T7m0qNSHZD

But what happens when we include time in the model? ⏳ Body size increases over the temporal range of our sample (1874 - 2003). Island individuals may be growing smaller over time (island rule reversal?), but sporadic island sampling makes it hard to confirm this (9/19) https://t.co/nOne7k6eib

Bergmann’s rule is reversed in mainland populations, though island individuals do show a slight increase in size w/ latitude. The rules are intertwined: island rule is upheld at higher, not lower, latitudes. No overall island effect on body size (8/19) https://t.co/wlf8uEhST7

...sexual size dimorphism (SSD) is controlled for in all analyses (and we also ran analyses on separate samples for each sex). We find that the degree of SSD varies significantly b/w mainland and island populations. Now onto the fun stuff! (7/19) https://t.co/Txlccie7fr

TLDR: no, they overlap completely in morphospace. We do not recognize T. b. chinensis as a subspecies and we treat our whole sample as one taxon (see supplementary info for more details on this). Next… (6/19) https://t.co/fayFaOFYWn

But first, we control for potential confounding factors: 1) infraspecific variation and 2) sexual dimorphism. Re: #1, this species’ taxonomic history is complicated. 27 synonyms and 2 subsp. recognized: T. b. belangeri + T. b. chinensis. Are they morphologically distinct? (5/19)

We collected 22 skull measurements from these specimens, imputed missing data, and performed a PCA (#RStats) to produce a proxy for body size (PC1) for each individual – which we then used to investigate size variation (4/19)

We tested these rules in the Northern Treeshrew (Tupaia belangeri), a tropical/subtropical SE Asian mammal. Our dataset is unprecedented in scope, spanning 21 latitudinal degrees + 130 years, including 839 museum specimens w/ associated historical climate + land-use data (3/19) https://t.co/ZRfnuQMEdF

Our study focuses on two well-known intraspecific body size trends: 1) Bergmann’s rule: size increases w/ latitude (as temp decreases); 2) Island (Foster's) rule: large mammals are smaller on islands relative to the mainland, and small mammals evolve the opposite pattern (2/19) https://t.co/bbTL8T1tMz

@daveregrets Which sucks for a whole variety of reasons.  Older forests = cheap and effective carbon capture, cleaner water, better habitat, etc...

@daveregrets I worry the conflation of capturing and storing more green carbon (and rebuilding carbon stores we lost from 150 years of OG logging) w/ offsets undermines support for forest carbon in general.

@daveregrets Protecting mature and old-growth forests on public lands, and encouraging longer logging rotations on private lands, should be base-line climate policy. They don't need to be linked to pollution credits.
Whereas WA rewards compliance by offering discounted instruments that hopefully also carry extra benefits
Like if you emit 106, you can pay $25 for the first 100, then $10 to "undo" the extra damage from the additional 6. It shouldn't be cheaper to correct an overage than to comply.

There is some logic to both systems, but WA's is more environmentally protective and follows a precautionary principle. And there is something perverse about the pricing in CA's system: you pay less to exceed the cap.
@daveregrets Thanks for saying this. It's so true.
In other words, in WA, offsets are a cheaper alternative to carbon credits. In CA, they are treated as negative emissions, which has been proven again and again to be false.
In CA, a compliance target of 100 can be met by emitting emitting 106, buying 100 credits and buying 6 offsets. In WA, it can be met by emitting 100, buying 94 credits and 6 offsets.

Reforms are possible -- plenty of good ideas out there -- but the most important one in my opinion would be for CA to follow WA's lead here and change how offsets factor into compliance with our cap and trade system.
Some, like Barbara Haya, have been banging this drum for longer than I have been involved in climate policy. She's always been right and more people should have listened.
Joining a growing chorus including @carbonplanorg @propublica and many others pointing to systemic failures in CA's forest offsets program.

Given the magnitude of the climate and ecological crisis, we already know that we need to prioritize research on climate change, and funding for it, much more. This is particularly true for economics. Policymakers and public funding organizations need to step up a great deal.

These results are only a tiny glimpse into the lack of funding for climate change research in economics. They might point to one of the reasons behind the ridiculously low number of economics journal articles on climate change which we examined here: https://t.co/Et1jWG0W91

In comparison to other topics it becomes clear that the amount of funding to climate change-related projects in the NSF economics programme is quite low. To illustrate, the NSF awards more grants on retirement and pensions than on climate change.

We find that less than 3% of all overall grants in the NSF economics programme have gone to climate change-related research. In terms of money, less than 5% of the budget was spent on climate change-related projects. Overall, the number of awards has even been going down. https://t.co/jBxY9JK4px

For the analysis we select all active and expired grants in the NSF economics programme between 1990 till 2021 and apply the following search string: "climate change", carbon, "global warming", "greenhouse gas".

But first, why care about funding? Public funding of research in economics is a crucial tool for policymakers to steer the direction of the discipline. It has an enormous signaling effect and can enable otherwise not feasible projects

(12/12) we can live in a greener, cleaner, more sustainable world without having to feel guilty for what has been literally a necessity in keeping our homes warm, bellies full and transport running.

(11/12) the main focus should be to help those that are affected most by climate change cope with its effects and make our energy generation more robust from both natural factors (solar storms) and provide energy security away from the oil cartels.

(10/12) this doesn’t mean we should continue to pollute the air and cut down trees. Clean air is good for our health and we need to sequester what we output. However we shouldn’t panic. We’re smart and adaptive as humans.

(9/12) we need to put in perspective that we are coming out of an ice age and have been for the last 12k years. Earth and humans have seen far higher CO2 levels and sea levels and have always adapted.

(8/12) furthermore governments should also aim to have all homes equipped with solar roofs. This starts with new builds and highly subsidised for those getting new roofs and/or a rewire of their homes.  Local councils should have solar on all govt buildings and public housing
(7/12) Govts can also help by subsidising public transport to make it more attractive than driving, this could mean free transport for those on lowest incomes

(6/12) it would also be a good idea to phase out grants and subsidies for fossil fuels and introduce a carbon tax but this should be done at a rate so as not to punish the poorest who can only afford petrol/diesel vehicles
(5/12) we should also be upgrading our grid anyway to deal with things like geomagnetic storms, EMPs, flood damage etc. partially this can be done with local storage rather than big power plants.
(4/12) obviously we should move away from fossil fuels as the fact is we’ll run out one day anyway. A combination of renewables and storage with a more resilient grid isn’t a bad thing.
(3/12) we should stop building on flood planes for obvious reasons and start to work more with nature rather than against it. (Mangroves on coasts etc)

(2/12) A lot of the change we will see with sea level rises will be very gradual and is something which can be resolved through a combination of….moving home (as we’ve done for tens of thousands of years) and putting in place better storm protection.

I am an environmental scientist but also a fen girl (born nr Kings Lynn). My family live in the fens & I am fully aware of the risks of climate change & the need to protect important agricultural land. But this is not the way to do it. We need to work with nature, not against it https://t.co/3UlYoDR0rf
This will have enormous consequences for wildlife by removing & changing habitats & food sources & fragmenting species ranges.

In conclusion. Mr Sutcliffes statement that the barrier will not interfere with the Wash is incorrect. By reducing the connection to the North Sea & adjoining coastline, it will change the water quality, sedimentary & hydrological processes of the system

Freshwater is also entering the Wash from the rivers. A barrier may reduce the salinity of the water, altering the distribution of species based on salinity tolerance, particularly small invertebrates that live in the mudflats. These are the primary food source for fish & birds. https://t.co/qf1mwJ2UoL

This will provide ideal conditions (warm, shallow, nutrient rich) for the development of large algal blooms & eutrophication. Algal blooms already occur in the Great Ouse estuary despite it being light-limited (turbid) https://t.co/eSaTg0gL3J

The Fens is an agricultural catchment – 89% is grade 1 or 2 agricultural land. In addition to sediment, the rivers contain high levels of nitrogen & phosphorus from fertiliser run-off. A tidal barrier will hold these nutrient rich waters in the Wash increasing the residence time https://t.co/4RW82smLHs

The Wash may start infilling with sediment from the rivers/estuaries, reducing mudflat & increasing saltmarsh. The proposed container port will need extensive & routine dredging to maintain. Re. issues with this & historic contaminants, look at the Tee's -https://t.co/Vc8anwu4zu

Any change in the movement of water and/or sediments into the wash and between the Wash and the North Sea will change the type and distribution of these habitats. A barrier across the Wash as proposed by Centre Port will do just this (artists impression from the website) https://t.co/N6J09XpmBW

The sediments (typically Pleistocene boulder clay) arrive via tidal currents (from deeper parts of the Wash and North Sea), longshore drift (from the Lincolnshire coast) and from the rivers/estuaries (Great Ouse, Nene, Witham and Welland)

These habitats are formed by the specific hydrology and geomorphology of the coastline – which determine how the water and sediments move around. The Wash is essentially a large bay, fed by a number of rivers/estuaries. Sediments settle here and form these varied habitats.

This is because it is has many habitats including mudflats sand dunes saltmarsh sand & shingle banks shallow & deep open water. These provide feeding roosting & breeding habitats for birds, but also support other species including a large population of common seals. https://t.co/XW3hwqr7Qz

Mr Sutcliffe is right that the Wash is an incredibly important area for biodiversity. It is arguably the most important site for birds in the UK and one of the most important wetlands for wildlife in Europe. https://t.co/cM2ks4134h

A statement reinforced by Chief Executive James Sutcliffe who said "We are saving the Wash. We're not interfering with it at all. It's still tidal, the salt marshes, the bird wading areas will all still be there”. So let’s critically evaluate this statement with science.

The Centre Port project is an 11-mile long structure and is proposed by the UK developer Port Evo. This is the mission statement. Note that guardianship and preservation of the ecology & natural habitat of the Wash is front and foremost https://t.co/YAUTenhunq

The technical assistance provided to #communities will allow #Batken residents to apply modern and affordable technologies in agriculture, increase yields and reduce agricultural losses, and strengthen and protect infrastructure facilities from disasters. https://t.co/8sTq5a9EmW

#Batken climate resilience has been strengthened through integrating solutions and expanding the application of #climatechange adaptation practices that were successfully implemented by UNDP in areas such as agriculture, integrated water💧 resources management, and DRR. https://t.co/JDDhOxNi2z

In 60 communities of Batken, Kadamjay, and Leilek regions water-saving drip irrigation systems were installed on 165.83 ha. The potential water savings in the rehabilitated area are 667,621 m3. The total cost of the activities was $261,236, of which 40% was farmers' contribution. https://t.co/bFu6iIcTQ7

The research was conducted to understand how #climatechange impacts #agriculture and #foodsecurity. Special research was held to remove obstacles faced by #women farmers to benefit from innovative measures of adaptation to climate change.Read the reports: https://t.co/lgcASvRb6X

Additional four #meteorological stations were successfully installed to improve the quality of meteorological forecasting. This will bring meteorological observations density to 60% (against 14,7% before) and enable more accurate and reliable forecasts in #Batken oblast. https://t.co/3fE878KDmf

Due to its low adaptive capacity, #Batken province is considered the most vulnerable to #climatechange impacts. In this regard, @undpkg selected areas to introduce climate-smart irrigation and mudflow protection measures in 60 local communities. https://t.co/ooXQ38YSd4

“I would be shocked if a La Niña happens for the fourth consecutive year,” Murtugudde said.
“Monsoon can be below normal by up to 15 per cent,” he pointed out. But this could change if the Arctic produces late-season heavy rainfall, similar to what happened between 2021-2022.
A neutral summer phase is usually bad news for India, Murtugudde said. India could see deficits in monsoon during this shift from La Niña winter to neutral summer.

Bleaching occurs when the water temperature rises too high, causing corals to expel the colorful algae that live in their tissues and turn white.
The reef is under threat from frequent bleaching events, including four in the last seven years and the first this year during a La Nina phenomenon, which typically brings cooler temperatures.
